"Grenz J.H., Sauerborn J.","Predicting the potential geographical distribution of parasitic weeds, a contribution to risk management: Case study of Orobanche crenata [Abschätzung der potentiellen geografischen verbreitung parasitischer unkräuter als beitrag zum risikomanagement: Fallstudie über Orobanche crenata]",2006,"Journal of Plant Diseases and Proctectio, Supplement",,"20",,"281","288",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34249284803&partnerID=40&md5=562050832ca4cf52e7979732ec6b488c","Institut für Pflanzenproduktion und Agrarökologie in Den Tropen und Subtropen, Universität Hohenheim, Garbenstraße 13, D-70599 Stuttgart, Germany","Grenz, J.H., Institut für Pflanzenproduktion und Agrarökologie in Den Tropen und Subtropen, Universität Hohenheim, Garbenstraße 13, D-70599 Stuttgart, Germany; Sauerborn, J., Institut für Pflanzenproduktion und Agrarökologie in Den Tropen und Subtropen, Universität Hohenheim, Garbenstraße 13, D-70599 Stuttgart, Germany","The potential distribution of the parasitic weed Orobanche crenata was studied in a combined literature, laboratory and simulation study. Populations of the root parasite only exist in regions with mediterranean climate, although individuals are able to reach maturity under conditions of temperate climate, too, and although O. crenata seeds can survive temperatures of -20°C. The dormancy behaviour of its seeds is likely to impede the northward spread of this species, since in a continuously moist environment, hardly any dormancy release takes place. Results of sensitivity analyses using simulation models suggest that a change to warmer and/or drier climate would substantially increase the risk of O. crenata establishment at higher latitudes. The collected information can, particularly when combined with data on host crop production, contribute to parasitic weed risk management. © Eugen Ulmer KG.","Dormancy; Geographical distribution; Global warming; Orobanche crenata; Parasitic weeds","geographical distribution; latitudinal gradient; Mediterranean environment; modeling; parasitic plant; prediction; risk assessment; seed dormancy; sensitivity analysis; temperature effect; weed; Orobanche; Orobanche crenata",,,,,,"BAR-NUN, N., MAYER, A.M., Preconditioning and germination of Orobanche seeds: Respiration and protein synthesis (1993) Phytochemistry, 34, pp. 39-45; BASKIN, C.C., BASKIN, J.M., (2001) Ecology, biogeography and evolution of dormancy and germination, , Academic Press, San Diego; BUSCHMANN, H., Hanftod, Tabakwürger - bald auch eine Bedrohung für den Raps? Das parasitische Unkraut Orobanche ramosa auf dem Vormarsch (2004) Gesunde Pflanzen, 56, pp. 39-47; COOKE, D., (2002) Control of Branched Broomrape, a Literature Review, , Animal and Plant Control Commission of South Australia; DRAKE, J.A., MOONEY, H.A., Biological invasions: A global perspective (1989) Scientific Committee on Problems of the Environment, , National Academy of Sciences. National Academy Press, Washington D.C; EPLEE, R., NORRIS, R., Prevention: A management strategy for parasitic weeds (1996) Advances in parasitic plant research. Proceedings of the 6th International Parasitic Weed Symposium. Dirección General de Investigación Agraria, pp. 755-759. , M.T. Moreno, J.I. Cubero Hrsg, Servicio de Publicaciones y Divulgación, Córdoba; FOY, C.F., RAKESH, J., JACOBSOHN, R., Recent approaches for chemical control of broomrape (Orobanche spp.) (1989) Reviews of Weed Science, 4, pp. 123-152; Global Biodiversity Information Facility in Sweden, Nordic Herbarium. Swedish Museum of Natural History, Stockholm (2005) Zugänglich, , www.gbif.se, GBIF:, unter; GRENZ, J., MANSCHADI, A.M., UYGUR, F.N., SAUERBORN, J., Effects of environment and sowing date on the competition between broad bean (Vicia faba) and the parasitic weed Orobanche crenata (2005) Field Crops Research, 93, pp. 300-313; JACOBSOHN, R., GREENBERGER, A., KATAN, J., LEVIN, M.A., ALON, H., Control of Egyptian Broomrape (Orobanche aegyptiaca) an